******
[1] Philippines (Countrywide)
Date: Mon 13 Oct 2014
Source: Outbreak News Today [abbreviated & edited]
http://healthmap.org/admin/disp.php?id=2860138


Even as the Philippines Department of Health saw great success with their mass measles and polio vaccination campaign, "Ligtas sa Tigdas," in which, as of 30 Sep 2014, the country's national coverage status reached 84 per cent (or 99.6 million people), the latest data from the World Health Organization (WHO) saw the number of cases increase by another 10 000 in September 2014. The Philippines has now seen 94 539 cases of the viral disease, up from 84 738 cases one month earlier.

During the same period in 2013, the Philippines saw 5763 confirmed cases. The WHO Measles-Rubella Bulletin for September 2014 says the country has seen 97 deaths due to measles. Only China has reported more measles cases (144 692) this year [2014], according to the WHO. The data from India have not been listed.

The disease is also called rubeola. Measles virus normally grows in the cells that line the back of the throat and lungs. Measles spreads through the air by breathing, coughing or sneezing. It is so contagious that any child who is exposed to it and is not immune will probably get the disease. Symptoms of measles include fever, runny nose, cough and a rash all over the body. About one out of 10 children with measles also gets an ear infection, and up to one out of 20 gets pneumonia. About one out of 1000 gets encephalitis, and one or 2 out of 1000 die.

[byline: Robert Herriman]

